<p><b>Madalyn Murray O'Hair</b> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1919-04-13"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="04-13"><a href="/wiki/April_13" title="April 13">April 13</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1919" title="1919">1919</a></span> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1995-09-29"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="09-29"><a href="/wiki/September_29" title="September 29">September 29</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1995" title="1995">1995</a></span>) was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Atheism" title="Atheism">atheist</a>. She was the founder of <a href="/wiki/American_Atheists" title="American Atheists">American Atheists</a> and, either openly or behind-the-scenes, was its President for 32 years from 1963 to 1995.</p>
<p>She is best known for the lawsuit, <i><a href="/wiki/Murray_v._Curlett" title="Murray v. Curlett" class="mw-redirect">Murray v. Curlett</a>,</i> which led to a landmark <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title="Supreme Court of the United States">Supreme Court</a> ruling and ended the practice of daily prayer in American public schools. O'Hair later founded <a href="/wiki/American_Atheists" title="American Atheists">American Atheists</a><sup id="cite_ref-about_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-about-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and became so controversial that, in 1964, <i><a href="/wiki/Life_(magazine)" title="Life (magazine)">Life</a></i> magazine referred to her as "the most hated woman in America."<sup id="cite_ref-time_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-time-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>She was murdered in 1995, along with her son and granddaughter, for reasons unrelated to her public image and activism.</p>
